{"cursor":"4461","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Christoph Adami |image = |image_size = 210px\n|caption = |birth_date = August 30, 1962 |birth_place = Brussels, Belgium\n|death_date = |death_place = |residence = United States |citizenship =\n|nationality = Germany |ethnicity = |fields = Evolutionary Biology and Physics\n|workplaces = Stony Brook University California Institute of\nTechnology Jet Propulsion Laboratory Keck Graduate Institute Michigan\nState University |alma_mater = University of Bonn Stony Brook University\n|doctoral_advisor =  |academic_advisors = Gerald E. Brown\n|doctoral_students = Charles Ofria |notable_students = |known_for = Negative\nquantum entropy Digital evolution Avida |author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = Fairchild Prize\nFellowship (1992) Caltech President's Fund Award (1996) NASA Exceptional\nAchievement Medal (2002) Fellow of the AAAS (2012) |religion = |signature =\n |footnotes = }} 'Christoph Carl Herbert Adami' is a\nprofessor of Microbiology and Molecular Genetics, as well as professor of\nPhysics and Astronomy, at Michigan State University. Adami was born August 30,\n1962 in Brussels, Belgium, and graduated from the European School of Brussels I.\nHe obtained a Diplom in Physics from the University of Bonn and an MA and a\nPh.D. in Theoretical Nuclear Physics from Stony Brook University in\n1991. He is best known for his work on Avida, an artificial life\nsimulator used to study evolutionary biology , and for applying the\ntheory of information to physical and biological systems. He is also an adviser\nto the Microbes Mind Forum.\n\n","linknr":138,"url":"Chris_Adami","recorded":1376416204,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Chris_Adami&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Chris_Adami&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/